div.lg:
The following is a collage of \skt{anuṣṭubh} elements, some of which attested in Indian Sanskrit literature, seemingly not all placed in the right metrical position, and with many other transgressions of the meter, most of which easily rectified. Only the syntactically necessary corrections are mentioned below. I may add here that \skt{me} no doubt needs to be supplied before \skt{vyapohantu} in l.~4.

maheśvara(m·)\footnote{\skt{maheśvara(m·)} \sep\ Finot notes that ``il y avait peut-être un \skt{m} ascrit à la suite de ce mot.'' It seems more than likely that the sign is indeed to be read as \skt{m·}.} umāñ ca agn[i]ñ ca\footnote{\skt{agn[i]ñ ca} \sep\ \skt{pra ...} Finot.}

 (bra)hmāṇaṃ viṣṇum\footnote{\skt{(bra)hmāṇaṃ viṣnum} \sep\ \skt{brahmāṇaṃ viṣṇum} Finot.} eva ca \\
namo prithivī\footnote{\skt{prithivī} \sep\ note the spelling; it seems uncertain to me whether the \skt{-ī} is long; read \skt{pṛthivīṃ}.} vāyur ākatham apa(ḥ)\footnote{\skt{ākatham apa(ḥ)} \sep\ understand \skt{ākāśam āpaḥ} with Finot. The akṣaras \skt{tha} and \skt{śa} are sufficiently similar to be confused, but one cannot here read \skt{śa} without emendation.}

 (jyo)tiś\footnote{\skt{(jyo)tiś} \sep\ ``Ce mot est peu distinct sur le fac-simile, mais il est à peu près sûr, d'après l'examen de la pierre'' Finot.} ca pañca\-mam· ; \\
namaskṛtvāham icchāmi sarvvaviśeṣair anudhyātam·\footnote{\skt{anudhyātam·} \sep\ read \skt{anudhyātaḥ}.} \\
\red{duṣkṛ}

\red{taṃ}\footnote{\skt{duṣkṛtaṃ} \sep\ \skt{duṣkṛ[tka]rmma} Finot.} vyapo\-ha\-n(tu) sukṛtena yunantu ca\footnote{\skt{sukṛtena yunantu ca} \sep\ \skt{sukṛto nayutantud(ā)} Finot. Finot comments: ``Bien que les lettres principales de cette ligne soient assez distinctes, le [\skt{sic}] lecture en est problématique, spécialement celle du mot que je lis, faute de mieux, \skt{nayutantudā} (= \skt{niyutaṃtudā}).'' The reading adopted here was proposed to me by Yuko Yokochi.} 
\end{stanzalist}

\noindent bhadreśvarasvāmipādānudhyātena\footnote{{\RC}\skt{pādānudhyātena} \sep\ {\RC}\skt{pādānudhyā(ne)na} Finot.} c[ā\-sm]ā\-ka[ṃ] mahārā[jñā]\footnote{\skt{mahārā[jñā]} \sep\ \skt{mahārā(jena)} Finot.} 

 [bha]\-dra\-va\-rmma\-ṇā manuṣyam adhruvaṃ\footnote{\skt{manuṣyam adhruvaṃ} \sep\ \skt{mānuṣyam adhvānaṃ} Finot.} jñā(tvā) bhadreśvarāya akṣayī nīvī dattā yathā pū(rvva)[taḥ]\footnote{\skt{(pūr)vva[taḥ]} \sep\ \skt{yathājñānam} Finot. Correction to \skt{pūrvveṇa} is implied in \BEFEO\ 18 n\up{o} 10, p.~14. C.~147, l.~1 indeed supports the latter reading, but there is no trace here of any \skt{e} joined to \skt{rvv}. So little is visible on stone and estampage that final the ending \skt{-taḥ} proposed here is only a diagnostic conjecture, in place of which \skt{-syām·} would be acceptable as well.} 

 (su)lahaparvvata\footnote{\skt{(su)lahaparvvata} \sep\ \skt{sulahaparvvato} Finot.} dakṣiṇena mahāparvvata\footnote{\skt{mahāparvvata} \sep\ \skt{mahāparvvataḥ} Finot.} paścimena ku\-co\-ka\-parvvata\footnote{\skt{kucoka}{\RC} \sep\ \skt{kucaka}{\RC} Finot. Cf.~C.~147, and Finot observation in \BEFEO\ 18 n\up{o} 10, p.~14 n.~2: ``J'avais lu précédemment \skt{Kucaka}, mais la voyelle \skt{o} est nettement indiquée sur la copie. Il s'agit sans doute d'un nom indigène, peut-être \skt{Ku \v c\switch{vietnam}{ơ}k}, «~l'auguste montagne~»''. From Finot's presentation of the matter, it is not clear whether this intends to correct his earlier reading of C.\ 72 or of C.\ 147, or both.} uttareṇa ma[hānadī]\footnote{\skt{ma[hānadī]} \sep\ \skt{ma[ryyādāḥ]} Finot. Cf.~C. 147, l.~4. Majumdar indeed reads \skt{ma(hānadī)}, but without any text-critical note.} 

 (pa)rimāṇābbhyantarā\footnote{\skt{(pa)rimāṇābbhyantarā} \sep\ \skt{parimānābhyantarā} Finot.} sa\-kuṭumbi\-janā bhūmi\footnote{\skt{bhūmi} \sep\ ``Lire \skt{bhūmir}; mais ce doit être une faute du texte, car il n'y a pas du \skt{d} redoublé'' Finot.} dattā ; janapadamaryyādā ṣa\red{ḍ}bhāge p\red{i \{2/3\}} 

 svāminā daśa\-bhāgenānu\-gṛhī\-tā devasya deya\footnote{\skt{deya} \sep\ \skt{dey(ā)} Finot.  I see no mark of \skt{ā}, but it must have been intended.} iti tad eva yathābhilikhitam akurvva[to] 

 (de)vasya ; janma\-pra\-bhṛti dharmmaprasavo yaḥ ; tatphalam bhadravarmmaṇaḥ\footnote{\skt{tatphalam bhadra}{\RC} \sep\ \skt{tatphalaṃ bhadra}{\RC} Finot.}~; yadi kaś cid a\-kram\-ya\footnote{\skt{akramya} \sep\ correct \skt{ākramya} with Finot.} hara(ti) 

 (vi)nāśayati vā~; muktadoṣā\footnote{\skt{muktadoṣā} \sep\ ``Il faudrait \skt{doṣāḥ}, mais il n'y a pas, dans le texte, place pour un visarga'' Finot.%checked that word visarga is in roman in original
} kuṭumbinaḥ ; tasyoparī a\-dharmma\footnote{\skt{adharmma} \sep\ ``Corr.\ \skt{adharmmaḥ}: même observation'' Finot.} syāt· ;  cāturvvaidyaṃ rājā\red{(naṃ)} 

 rājamātram bā\footnote{\skt{rājā(naṃ) rājamātram bā} \sep\ \skt{rājā\red{naṃ}  rājamātraṃ vā} Finot. Finot's reading is intended. Cf.~Vālmīki's Rāmāyaṇa 2.94.19: \skt{eko 'py amātyo medhāvī śūro dakṣo vicakṣaṇaḥ~| rājānaṃ rāja\-mātraṃ vā prāpayen mahatīṃ śriyam}.} saha kuṭumbi\-bhiḥ ; vijñā\-pa\-yāmi mamānukampārtthaṃ\footnote{{\RC}\skt{nukampārtthaṃ} \sep\ {\RC}\skt{nukampārthaṃ} Finot.} yan mayā dattaṃ mā vināśaya(tha)\footnote{\skt{vināśaya(tha)} \sep\ \skt{vin(āśa)ya(ta)} Finot. If the ending -\skt{tha} is indeed what has been engraved, it must be emended to -\skt{ta}.}

\subsection*{{\skt{Face B}}}	

 yadi vināśayatha janmani janmani vo yat sukṛtaṃ tan mama syāt·

 yac ca mama duṣkritaṃ\footnote{\skt{duṣkritaṃ} \sep\ \skt{duṣkṛtaṃ} Finot.} tad yuṣmākaṃ\footnote{	\skt{yuṣmākaṃ} \sep\ \skt{yuṣm(ā)kaṃ} Finot. The \skt{ā} seems visible on the estampage.} syā(t)· ; atha samyak paripālayatha tad yu\-ṣma\-kam ava\footnote{\skt{yuṣmakam ava} \sep\ \skt{yuṣmakam eva} Finot; corr.\ \skt{yuṣmākam eva}.} 

 dharmma\footnote{\skt{dharmma} \sep\ ``Même observation'' Finot.} syād iti ; bhūyo vijñāyāmi\footnote{\skt{vijñāyāmi} \sep\ ``Corr.\ \skt{vijñāpayāmi}'' Finot. It is also necessary to restore \skt{yam} after this verb form.}~; ya iha prabhavati~; ete\footnote{\skt{ete} \sep\ ... Finot.} devam[u](ṣṭ)ikārakāḥ\footnote{\skt{devam[u](ṣṭ)ikārakāḥ} \sep\ \skt{devabalikārakāḥ} Finot (with indication that the reading is uncertain).} [te]

[ṣā]ṅ karmma na kārayitavyaṃ~; syāc cora\-bha\-ya(ṃ) skandhāvāratvaritaṃ\footnote{\skt{syāc corabhaya(ṃ) skandhāvāratvaritaṃ} \sep\ \skt{syād . ora............ ratrarataṃ} Finot. Correct °\skt{skandhāvāraduritaṃ}.} vā rājakulakāryyam anuṣṭheya[m·] \{2 akṣ.\}\footnote{\skt{anuṣṭheya[m·] \{2 akṣ.\}} \sep\ \skt{anuṣṭheyam..} Finot.} 

 \red{macaguro}\footnote{\skt{macaguro} \sep\ \skt{atha guro} Finot.} smākaṃ rājānam·\footnote{\skt{rājānam·} \sep\ \skt{rājān(o)..} Finot.} ; yat kiñcit puṣpaphalaṅ gṛhyaṃ\footnote{\skt{kiñcit puṣpaphalaṅ gṛhyaṃ} \sep\ \skt{kiñcit... phalāḍhyeṣu} Finot.} pāde\red{(ṣu)} pa\-di\-ta\-vyam\footnote{\skt{pāde(ṣu) paditavyam} \sep\ or read \skt{pāde apaditavyam}? I tentatively propose to emend \skt{pāditavyam} (or \skt{apāditavyam}).} iti 

 me\footnote{\skt{iti me} \sep\ although no traces of lost akṣaras are visible at the end of l.~5 or the beginning of 6, it seems that possibly \skt{ye} must be restored between these two words.} mahilaputra\red{natakapana(tṛ)kajāmāduko}\footnote{\skt{°natakapana(tṛ)kajāmāduko} \sep\  This sequence is certainly corrupt. Yuko Yokochi has made the convincing suggestion to me of reading \skt{°naptṛkapranaptṛkajāmātṛkān}. While what is readable on the stone cannot be read as such, it may be supposed that a reading such as that proposed by Yokochi stood in a source of which the composer of our inscription has access to an itself already corrupt copy.} vā vijñāpayāmi~; yaṃ\footnote{\skt{yaṃ} \sep\ correct \skt{yan}.} mayā kṛta\footnote{Line 6 was left entirely unread by Finot, who merely notes: ``Environ 27 askṣaras [\skt{sic}]'' Finot.}

[m a]nupālaye(ta) vaḥ ; iha paratra ca\footnote{\skt{[m a]nupālaye(ta) vaḥ ; iha paratra ca} \sep\ \skt{kuśalāyatanāḥ ; vahularatnaca} Finot. Understand \skt{anupālyeta}?}~; ma(ma ka)rmma(pha)laṃ bhaviṣyati ; tubh(y)aṃ prabhāva\footnote{Finot only read the first 12 akṣaras of this line. For the rest, he noted: ``Environ 16 askṣaras [\skt{sic}].''} 

 \red{.... ahannisvāret(o)\footnote{\skt{.... ahannisvāret(o)} \sep\ \skt{.... ayan na svarato} Finot. Finot notes the loss of ``Environ 18 askṣaras [\skt{sic}]'' before his \skt{ayan}.} ;} dharmmo bhavi\-ṣya\-ti\footnote{\skt{dharmmo bhaviṣyati} \sep\ \skt{dharmmabhava.....} Finot.} 

 (ya anu)\-pālayati\footnote{\skt{(ya anu)pālayati} \sep\ \skt{ ...... pālayati} Finot.} tasyaiṣa dharmmo\footnote{\skt{dharmmo} \sep\ \skt{dharmma(ḥ)} Finot.} yo nānupālati\footnote{\skt{nānupālati} \sep\ \skt{na tu pālati} Finot. ``Corr.\ \skt{pālayati}'' Finot.} ; mā vi\-nā\-śa\-ya\-tu\footnote{\skt{mā vināśayatu} \sep\ \skt{abhināśayatu} Finot.} ; atha vi\-nā\-śa\-yati 

 tasya bhadreśvarasvāmi\footnote{{\RC}\skt{svāmi} \sep\ corr.\ {\RC}\skt{svāmī}.} jānāti\footnote{Finot observes that the text seems to end abruptly.}                  
